\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/mf.maass.exceptional_eigenvalue}{Exceptional eigenvalues of Maass forms}}
\begin{definition}\label{mf.maass.exceptional_eigenvalue}
\uses{mf.maass.mwf,mf.maass.mwf.eigenvalue,mf.maass.mwf.spectralparameter}
Each \hyperref[mf.maass.mwf.eigenvalue]{eigenvalue} $\lambda$ of a \hyperref[mf.maass.mwf]{Maass form} can be written as $\lambda = \frac{1}{4} + R^2$, where $R$ is the \hyperref[mf.maass.mwf.spectralparameter]{spectral parameter}.
Each eigenvalue is real and nonnegative, and the spectral parameter is either purely real or purely imaginary.

If $R$ is purely real (so $0 < \lambda < \frac{1}{4}$), then $\lambda$ is called \textbf{exceptional}. No exceptional eigenvalues are known. Selberg conjectured that they don't exist [Sel65].

[Sel65]: Selberg, Atle (1965), "On the estimation of Fourier coefficients of modular forms", in Whiteman, Albert Leon (ed.), Theory of Numbers, Proceedings of Symposia in Pure Mathematics, vol. VIII, Providence, R.I.: American Mathematical Society, pp. 1â€“15.
\end{definition}


